The Herald Arts Reporter
The National Arts Council of Zimbabwe (NACZ) has announced Derwin Guti as the winner of the #Nama legends@40 Trophy Design Competition. His trophy design was found by the adjudication committee to be well thought out, in support of the theme and the design identified with the programme and the organisation. <img class="wp-image-529081 size-large" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2021/02/Untitled-6-3-480x680.jpg" alt="" width="480" height="680" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2021/02/Untitled-6-3-480x680.jpg 480w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2021/02/Untitled-6-3-254x360.jpg 254w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2021/02/Untitled-6-3.jpg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px" /> Derwin Guti The shape of the trophy and its opening at the stand base is quite creative and makes it unique, NACZ said. Guti, whose design was selected ahead of 10 other entries from designers across the country, is a 25-year-old residing in Harare who is into fine art, specialising in ballpoint-pen drawings.